reviews.text:
Beautiful church attached to the Tyrolean Museum.
The tomb for Maximilian is really cool with all the the life size status surrounding it.
While I was there a gentleman was playing the organ in the small hall on the second floor
Wonderful and beautiful church.  It appears to have had sign hurricane renovation.  The colors are amazing
This is a beautiful location and impressive to see. We did a combo with the museum next door and it was a highlight of the city.
Amazing place to visit. Lovely place
Really amazing place, dont miss the video/fantasy show explaining the story briefly available in both English and German language.
Really nice and beautiful church. It's full of light and I love it.
very impressive architecture. only pity that when I was there, there was an iron gate a few meters into the church which prevented you from walking any further. you can only gaze through that gate.
Very beautiful sanctuary

This Baroque basilica is certainly magnificent inside, belying its rather ordinary exterior. I'll add some photos to give you an idea of the interior because words are useless. The only reason that I don't give it 5 stars is because when we visited we were stuck in the antechamber (is that the right word? Probably not.) staring through wire mesh at all the opulent ornamentation. As a keen amateur photographer this really irritated me because so many excellent shots were being denied to me. My whinge aside, if you are in the area you MUST visit. Especially if you like historic grandeur and photography.
Super
What a wonderful place! Definitely worth a stop if you are in the area. And the nature around the castle is so beautiful as well.
Very beautiful. Good collection of arms and other artefacts of those times. Good garden and walkways to roam around. Surprise was peacocks and white peacock too..

We spent about 90 minutes exploring this site. It was very interesting and the grounds would be beautiful in the summer. I would recommend it as part of the Innsbruck card package along with the sightseer bus.
Nice to visit in a morning or afternoon and walk around or relax. The restaurant is very nice
Very nice expositions. Beautiful view. 12€ per adult. The parking is not free, 0.7€/h

Nice spot to see the whole view of the area. It’s narrow on top but comfortable enough to walk around without bag. If you have backpack it might not comfortable for other to walk pass you at the top area. The view from there is pretty good.

I came to Innsbruck during Christmas so I got to experience the Christmas market and the crowds. It was fun and different. During the evening when I was there (a few days before Christmas) we were serenaded by a brass quartet from the Golden Roof. I’m not sure if you can go inside but it was a sight to view from the outside. Hotel rooms on the Main Street there also have a great view of the Golden Roof.

Interesting history of this building with the Golden Roof over the balcony. Looking out onto a small square which was full of Xmas markets and a giant Xmas Tree. The atmosphere is wonderful with lots of people, interesting smells from the many food and beverage stalls a moving light projection onto the surrounding buildings and 5 or more musicians playing Xmas Carol's from the Golden Roof balcony. We came here at least once every day we were in in Innsbruck as the atmosphere was so wonderful. Unfortunately the museum in the building was closed during the time we were there.
Amazing history and quality exhibits that also catered for kids. Get the Innsbruck card so you can see this and other local museums for free.
What a lovely evening walk. I just love the overall ambience. Maybe it's because I visited at a convenience situation and time.

One arch is much like the next one to most of us, but this one at least provides some additional interest with its somewhat tragic history. One one side, this may be a triumphal arch, but on the other, it is quite the opposite. It is worth checking out and learning the history behind the decorations. You probably won't be able to avoid it in any case, thanks to the central location.

I have been 3 times hoping to go up. Never once was i able. Can't even figure out how to cross underneath. 

Its beautiful but thats it from me.
A must-see landmark during your stay in Innsbruck. Build to honor the prince's marriage and his father's death.
Great monument which has great views of Nordkette and the Bergisel ski jump
Innsbruck is a lovely mountain town with great architecture!
It’s very small museum but learned how bells are made. Learning the process and the materials used was interesting. Definitely worth going if you are walking towards ski jump, panorama museum, etc.

One of the best museums I've been to. Caters for English language speakers too. Family run, friendly place and they showed us the blessing and pouring of a bell too! This was followed by traditional post-bell pouring schnapps. Excellent museum, couldn't recommend more highly!
Nice lil Museum. Shows the work about bells. A must see in Innsbruck!
Nice place. Great attention
Guide talked really slow... Like we are stupid or something

This place was disappointing. We were surprised that a new museum didn't have English subtitles. I am sure it is a fascinating collection but we didn't know the significance of what we seeing. The panorama is a 10 minute visit. On the positive side, the restaurant 1809 was great. Service was quick. Food was great. Value reasonable. I would recommend the restaurant.

Got free entry as part of the Innsbruck Card, and glad it was free as I wouldn’t have been happy paying the €8 fee. The museum has some interesting displays, such as stuffed animals (including a bear) and a retro ski gondola cab, as well as many other random trinkets and displays. However, none of these items have any English translations on their info cards, which I found quite strange for a fairly new looking attraction, as a majority of the other attractions I’ve been to in Innsbruck have multi-lingual displays. The panorama itself is fantastic, with added props to give it a great 3D effect. This place is probably great with lots to learn if you speak/read German, however as an English speaking tourist, I was left a little disappointed.
Worth going up the hill, don't forget to go to Bergisel ski jump.

Wow!.........war, Europeans really liked to fight. The panorama is a 360 degree mural depicting an intense battle between the people of Tyrol and the Austrian army for the ''freedom'' of Tyrol (felt more like a civil war to me). A conventional army in battle against a rag tag band of local inhabitants, modern weapons vs anything you could find set in the Napoleonic era

A fantastic place to visit on a clear blue sky. Park close by and visit the museums, the cafe or walk up to the ski jump. Views northwards over Innsbruck to the NordKette and east / west down the Inn valley. Stunning.

Nice spot to see the whole view of the area. It’s narrow on top but comfortable enough to walk around without bag. If you have backpack it might not comfortable for other to walk pass you at the top area. The view from there is pretty good.

During the evening when I was there (a few days before Christmas) we were serenaded by a brass quartet from the Golden Roof. I’m not sure if you can go inside but it was a sight to view from the outside. Hotel rooms on the Main Street there also have a great view of the Golden Roof.

The atmosphere is wonderful with lots of people, interesting smells from the many food and beverage stalls a moving light projection onto the surrounding buildings and 5 or more musicians playing Xmas Carol's from the Golden Roof balcony. We came here at least once every day we were in in Innsbruck as the atmosphere was so wonderful. Unfortunately the museum in the building was closed during the time we were there.

What a lovely evening walk. I just love the overall ambience. Maybe it's because I visited at a convenience situation and time.

Old and beautiful tower in Innsbruck. Town Tower is located in the old center of Innsbruck, near the building of the golden roof, the tower was used by the guards to watch over the city. . To climb the tower are 133 steps, to have a very nice view of the city and the Alps.
Amazing architecture, this city is great. It’s a bit pricey, of course. Would love to come back
Beautiful scenery from above. Included in Innsbruck Card.
Nice views and surely worth the climb. 4€ is a bit steep though for having to climb 133 steps.
Nice and quite place lots of cafe shops around the place

Interesting museum for sure. Worth the visit to check out all of the old artifacts from Austrian life. The have a rotating exhibit on the 3rd floor too. It was about smoking on my trip. 
Fun to walk into al the old, wooden parlors too.
Connected to the Church, so easy to do both in one.

Super interesting museum: besides a huge collection of everyday objects and furniture, it has an amazing set of 19 “parlours”, the wood-paneled reception rooms where families received people into their homes and spent most of the time in, from Gothic to Baroque period. It’s an eerie and immersive experience to be in them, perfectly reconstructed. Speaking of immersion, the museum does a great job in creating an atmosphere by grouping objects (and human-sized figures) to tell the story of the periods, and it’s right next door to the Court Church (with the “black statues”), including a passage that allows for a view from the choir of the church. Super recommended!

We dropped in on a visit to the Hofkirche next door and decided to visit this museum. What an unexpected treat it was. We loved it. There was so much to look at but the highlight to us were the authentic "stubes" or rooms. It was fascinating to see how homes were arranged throughout the ages. Well done! It was a highlight of my visit to the city.
Very nice museum! Near the centre

Eighty years after it was founded, the museum in Universitätsstrasse underwent substantial reconstruction in 2008/2009 and now has a new look. Lucifer is the ‘light-bearer’ who guides visitors through the ‘new’ Museum of Tyrolean Folk Art. He is the agent provocateur, the enfant terrible in our brave, seemingly well-ordered museum world. He asks questions, casts doubts, and undermines: what is art? What is craft? What is real? What only seems to be? Lucifer devotes himself to reality.

The varied exhibition areas include ‘Miniaturen des Evangeliums’ [‘Gospel Miniatures’] (cribs), ‘Pralles Jahr’ [‘Year Full to Bursting’], ‘Prekäres Leben’ [‘Perilous Life’], ‘Schein und Sein’ [‘Illusion and Reality’] (traditional costumes), the Studiensammlung [collection of studies], and the Stuben [parlours]. Visitors are also ‘prepared’ for the Court Church by an impressive preview.

The Museum of Tyrolean Folk Art in Innsbruck is one of the most beautiful of its kind in Europe. In 1888, the Tyrolean trade association decided to build a ‘Tyrolean trade museum’ in Innsbruck. Initially, exemplary crafted contemporary products were collected. They were meant to give Tyrolean craftsmen new ideas.

Later, “Old Tyrolean arts and crafts as well as the products of domestic Tyrolean diligence” were also included in the collection. The collection of the ‘Tyrolean museum for folk art and trade’ (1903), which was then owned by the chamber of trade and commerce, was afterwards relocated to the former Franciscan monastery that still houses it today. In 1926, the Tyrolean chamber of trade and commerce handed the exhibits over to the County of Tyrol, obliging the county to “set them up in a publicly accessible museum”.

In 1929, the Museum of Tyrolean Folk Art—as it was henceforth called—was opened. Many of its objects had been purchased prior to World War I. They came from the old County of Tyrol, including the Province of Trento (southern part of the historic Trentino region), and the Ladin valleys around the Dolomites. The collection items belong to various social strata: the peasantry, the middle classes, and the nobility. The collection is centred on artisan craftwork, applied arts, domestic industry, popular piety, masks, and traditional costumes.

Among the best botanical gardens in the world. Interesting outdoor spaces but also many indoor collections if you are visiting on a rainy day. Wonderful collection of cacti. Beautiful nature paths. Definitely a worthy part of any visit to Berlin.

This was the best botanical garden that i have visited during early Spring. Its very well priced and the glass houses were brilliant, ferns, cactus, Tropical, so many different rooms and each was throughly enjoyed. 
Take a picnic if the weather if good and even a few beers like i saw some locals. 
The coffee shop also serves lovely cold, big beers) Thumbs up on that and the gift shop has some lovely items.

The outside grounds weren't quite in bloom yet but they were still beautiful. The many and massive greenhouses were amazing. Different regions of the world, different climates and all were meticulously cared for.

Beautiful Botanical garden. They have plants from all continents. It is also interesting in winter time because the glasshouses with plants are huge. So you don't have to be afraid that you wont have anything to see if it's winter.

It is my most visited place in Berlin. I had two times a year ticket and I used it many times. I was there in average 2 times a week. 

The vegan soup is awesome! The houses are the perfect friend in winter months. The gardens are great for the summer. 

For all touristic and local interest's important place! 

You can walk by food from breitenbachplatz
What a fantastic find. The groestl is one I want to write home and tell the world about. Schnitzel and potato salad was also pretty remarkable. Martin gave us great recommendations!
Good food and service but they don't have chairs for children
Food quite good and waiter is quite interesting
Great place! Our waiter was very friendly, and helped us decide what to get. The food was delicious, and the portions were quite large. I got the mixed grill plate and was very satisfied.
Service is great, kassspatzl ok

The restaurant is not in the best position to attract customers, but has beautiful, delicious and authentic Indian food. The service was very uplifting and friendly which complimented well with their flavoursome dishes we ordered. 
Overall my family and I were very impressed and satisfied with the food and service the restaurant had to offer. I would highly recommend them to locals and tourists.

Stopped in while on a day trip to Innsbruck and was so glad I did! Quaint family-run restaurant who were eager to please with some of the best Indian food I've ever had.
As a group we got several lamb dishes that were nothing short of excellent. You could cut the lamb with a spoon it was so tender!
If you're in Innsbruck and craving great Indian food I couldn't recommend a better spot!

I stopped at the restaurant a few years ago during a tour of Europe. 
 Welcoming atmosphere. Staff is very warm and friendly. Food is quite good for the price. Overall, worth the visit. Do stop by if in Innsbruck.
Food is the worst. Felt sick for days after eating my lunch from here. Staff were extremely ride

I wish I could give this rating in negative. Such a horrible experience. Unhealthy, unhygienic, tasteless & stale food. This restaurant should be closed right away. The owner and his wife ( I think) were so rude. I was asked to take my baby out until the food is ready just because she was playing around. They don’t accept card, doing business illegal. No proper invoice was given. We didn’t eat any of the dishes. DONT VISIT THIS RESTAURANT. GUYS BEWARE!!!
Very good food and service
The best affordable place in Las Mercedes
Excelent place to eat Italian food
The best pizza in Mercedes neighborhood.
good for pizzas

I had a really pleasant evening there. I really liked the interior and the seating.

The service was really good, they have been really helpful and friendly. The ask twice if everything is okay but not too often just perfect to reorder drinks.

The pizza could be more tasty but i really enjoyed it though. I would love to see buffalo mozzarella on the menu.

Would recommend this location.

Love this place.Feels like a little slice of Italy.Food is delicious,really fresh ingredients,service is super friendly and it's got a great atmosphere.Really super value wel.Recommend We had a great night, were made to feel very welcome and would recommend this restaurant. The food was fantastic! My new Italian home. Too good, too friendly. I'm looking forward to joining the family. The food was amazing. pizzas were good and the wine as well, came here after a day in Innsbruck. Good restaurant in a great little city
Quite good pizza, but wouldnt make it in top 2 pizza places of Innsbruck..
High class & quality

Had a lovely meal with family. We tried the pasta with shrimp and rocket, regatoni with aubergine and tomato, gnoccetti with tomato sauce and salad. Good wine too. All very happy and no room for dessert this time. A reasonably priced meal. 
The two staff were polite and helpful, especially since they were OK speaking English with us.
